                        <h1>Trend project</h1>
                        <p>Tanzania Rural Enterprises Network for Development (TREND) is yet another project aimed at empowering the economic poor through promotion of &ldquo;fair trade&rdquo;. The aim of TREND is to support subsistence farmers by ensuring that they receive a better market share and bargain for their products. This project will also help the community to improve the quality of their product and scale up their methods of farming, producing, packaging and delivery. Pilot projects have currently been launched for products such as honey and intend to unveil sesame seeds and sunflower within the near future.</p>
                        <h2>Beekeeping</h3>
                        <p>Tanzania only produces 9000MT of its capacity of 138000 MTs of bee honey production. The global demand has increased by 10% to a staggering 154 million MT per year by 2010. The value of honey has also increased by 30% over the last 3 years as honey production in Europe is declining. Hence African honey has a brighter future.<br /> <br /> The Eco Village situated in Mukuranga district around 50 km from the capital Dar es Salaam is surrounded by lush green landscape and has a large potential for beekeeping. However as many areas of Tanzania it is considered a novel idea and hence many have not explored its potential. The farmers who are keeping bees lack appropriate technology to increase their production and to ensure appropriate quality for export.<br /> <br /> Understanding this lack of supply and high demand Islamic Help Tanzania intends to set up a modern intensive beekeeping project in its Eco Village farm. The investment is <span class="red">13,000,000 Tshs</span>. The investor/ donor can be a partner or can contribute as cash Waqf which will give regular income for supporting the orphan children in the eco village</p>
                        <img src='images/slides/economic/trend.png' alt='' width='100'/>
                        <p>Islamic Help Tanzania&rsquo;s main aim is to supply quality bulk honey to the UK and Middle East. Islamic Help have been registered as an exporter and are now seeking potential buyers on internet portals as well as forums. Islamic Help have also linked with Honey king a Chinese venture to supply honey in case of over production and have built rapport with the Ministry for Natural resources to start a network with local beekeepers in Kilwa, Kisarawe , Mukuranga and Pangani. Islamic Help hope to set up similar projects within these districts and also purchase from local beekeepers; expecting&nbsp; a of supply 10MTs by 2017</p>
